.TH _PRINTF 3 "18 Nov 2025" "Custom C Library" "Holberton School"
.SH NAME
_printf \- a custom printf function in C.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"

int _printf(const char *format, ...);

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf()
function prints text based on a format string.  
The format string can contain normal characters, which are printed as they are, and
format specifiers, which are replaced by values passed to the function.

.SH SUPPORTED CONVERSION SPECIFIERS
.TP
.B c
Prints a character from an int value.

.TP
.B s
Prints a null-terminated string.

.TP
.B %
Prints the % character itself.

.TP
.B d, i
Prints an int as a signed decimal number.

.TP
.B b
Prints an unsigned int in binary.

.TP
.B u
Prints an unsigned int in decimal (unsigned format).

.TP
.B o
Prints an unsigned int in octal.

.TP
.B x
Prints an unsigned int in hexadecimal (lowercase).

.TP
.B X
Prints an unsigned int in hexadecimal (uppercase).

.TP
.B S
Prints a string, replacing non-printable characters
(ASCII < 32 or >= 127) with \x followed by two uppercase hex digits.

.TP
.B r
Prints the reversed version of a string.

.TP
.B p
Prints a pointer address in hexadecimal.

.SH RETURN VALUES
The function returns the number of characters printed.  
A negative value is returned if an error happens.

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
_printf("Character: %c\n", 'A');
Output: Character: A

.TP
_printf("String: %s\n", "Hello");
Output: String: Hello

.TP
_printf("Integer (d): %d\n", 98);
Output: Integer (d): 98

.TP
_printf("Integer (i): %i\n", -42);
Output: Integer (i): -42

.TP
_printf("Percent sign: %%\n");
Output: %

